.govuk-grid-row
  .govuk-grid-column-two-thirds
    %h1.govuk-heading-xl Accessibility Statement

    %p.govuk-body This accessibility statement applies to the View Court Data online service (abbreviated to VCD).

    %p.govuk-body This website is run by the Legal Aid Agency (LAA). We want as many people as possible to be able to use this website. For example, that means you should be able to:

    %ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      %li navigate VCD using speech recognition software
      %li navigate VCD using a keyboard
      %li change colours, contrast levels and fonts using browser or device settings
      %li listen to most of the website using a screen reader (including the most recent versions of JAWS, NVDA and VoiceOver) - see exceptions below

    %p.govuk-body We've also made the website text as simple as possible to understand.

    %p.govuk-body
      %a.govuk-link{ href: "https://mcmw.abilitynet.org.uk/" } AbilityNet
      has advice on making your device easier to use if you have a disability.

    %h2.govuk-heading-m How accessible this website is

    %p.govuk-body We know some parts of this website are not fully accessible:

    %ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      %li On any page with pagination, the content between the first and last buttons isn't being displayed on mobile devices, or when 400% zoom is applied.
      %li On two pages, there are areas that are not currently being read out by screen reader software.
      %li A small amount of text does not allow extra spacing to be applied to it.
      %li When the website is zoomed in to 400%, some content breaks out of its containers and overlaps other elements.
      %li Some values are not being read out in an optimum way by screen reader software.
      %li The accordion component (which is minimised on load and expands to show more content) is very difficult to use with screen reader software.
      %li Some headers are not currently tagged correctly in the code.
      %li Some URLs and page titles are currently inconsistent or apply to multiple pages.
      %li There are some validation issues in the code.
      %li Some content needs to be reworded so that it is read out in a more concise manner by a screen reader. This is not a Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) failure, but is notable enough to mention.
      %li On the 'Manage users' page, you have to navigate back to the top of the filter component to apply filters after selecting their options. This is not a Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) failure, but is notable enough to mention.
      %li Also on the 'Manage users' page, you have to tab through a lot of unnecessary elements that shouldn't be links. This is not a Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) failure, but is notable enough to mention.

    %h2.govuk-heading-m Reporting accessibility problems with this website

    %p.govuk-body
      We're always looking to improve the accessibility of this website. If you find any problems not listed on this page or think we're not meeting accessibility requirements, contact
      %a.govuk-link{ href: "mailto:mojprod@service-now.com" } mojprod@service-now.com
      on Teams or via email.

    %h2.govuk-heading-m Enforcement procedure

    %p.govuk-body
      The Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) is responsible for enforcing the Public Sector Bodies (Websites and Mobile Applications) (No. 2) Accessibility Regulations 2018 (the 'accessibility regulations'). If you're not happy with how we respond to your complaint,
      %a.govuk-link{ href: "https://www.equalityadvisoryservice.com/" } contact the Equality Advisory and Support Service (EASS)
      \.

    %h2.govuk-heading-m Technical information about this website's accessibility

    %p.govuk-body The Legal Aid Agency (LAA) is committed to making its website accessible, in accordance with the Public Sector Bodies (Websites and Mobile Applications) (No. 2) Accessibility Regulations 2018.

    %h2.govuk-heading-m Compliance status

    %p.govuk-body The website has been tested against the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.2 AA standard.

    %p.govuk-body
      This website is partially compliant with the
      %a.govuk-link{ href: "https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG22/" } Web Content Accessibility Guidelines version 2.2
      AA standard, due to the non-compliances listed below.

    %h2.govuk-heading-m Non-accessible content

    %p.govuk-body The content listed below is non-accessible for the following reason(s):

    %ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      %li On any page with pagination, such as the 'Manage users' page, the content between the first and last buttons isn't being displayed on mobile devices, or when 400% zoom is applied. You can only navigate between the screens using the previous and next buttons. This fails WCAG 2.2 success criterion 2.4.5 (multiple ways). We plan to fix this issue so that everyone can navigate using the number buttons as well as the previous/next buttons.
      %li On two pages, there are areas that are not currently being read out by screen reader software; the content in the Hearings table on the 'Breaches' overview page, and everything after the first calendar date selector on the 'Linking Data' page. This fails WCAG 2.2 success criterion 1.3.2 (meaningful sequence). We plan to fix this issue so that all content is read out by a screen reader, and will test all new pages with a screen reader in future.
      %li A small amount of text throughout the website does not allow extra spacing to be applied to it. This fails WCAG 2.2 success criterion 1.4.12 (text spacing). We plan to fix this so that spacing can be applied to all text.
      %li When the website is zoomed in to 400%, some content breaks out of its containers and overlaps other elements. This especially applies to wide tables, banners, and the two-column layout on 'Hearing' pages. This fails WCAG 2.2 success criterion 1.4.10 (reflow). We plan to fix this so that all content is fully viewable without any overlapping.
      %li The accordion component (which is minimised on load and expands to show more content) is very difficult to use with screen reader software. The content inside the element is not read out even if you open it before the screen reader reaches that section of the page - therefore, you have to reload the page and have all content be read out a second time to actually hear the content inside the accordion. This fails WCAG 2.2 success criterion 1.3.2 (meaningful sequence). We plan to redesign the 'Hearing' pages, remove any key content from accordions and display them in a more accessible component instead. We will also not use any other minimise/maximise components going forward.
      %li Some headers are not currently tagged correctly in the code (as &lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt;, &lt;h3&gt;, and so on), so they are less likely to be announced or mapped properly by assistive software. This fails WCAG 2.2 success criterion 2.4.10 (section headings). We plan to check our code and fix anything that isn't currently tagged correctly.
      %li Some URLs and page titles are currently inconsistent or apply to multiple pages, which can confuse assistive technology, create incorrect bookmarks, and increase cognitive load for users. This fails WCAG 2.2 success criterion 2.4.2 (page titled). We plan to check our code and fix anything that isn't currently indexed correctly.

    %h2.govuk-heading-m What we're doing to improve accessibility

    %p.govuk-body Our accessibility audit report shows how and when we plan to improve accessibility on this website, with an outline of journeys both before and after changes have been made.

    %h2.govuk-heading-m Preparation of this accessibility statement

    %p.govuk-body This statement was prepared on 17th February 2026. It was last reviewed on 26th February 2026. The aim is that it will be reviewed quarterly.

    %p.govuk-body This website was last tested on 15th January 2026 against the WCAG 2.2 AA standard.

    %p.govuk-body The test was carried out by the LAA. The most viewed pages were tested using automated and manual testing tools internally. A further audit of the website was carried out to the WCAG 2.2 AA standard.
